rs resisted the state's educational initiatives and identified with the independent farm movement. In order to ensure the success of the WI the Ontario Department of Agriculture provided funds to hire organizers and the organization was encouraged to develop branches outside farming areas, even if this meant ignoring the needs of farm women. By the end of the World War I the WI had become one of the largest women's organizations in the province but was widely known not for its emphasis on scientific home management but for its community activism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFemmes en milieu ruralxAssociationsxHistoirexOntario. 0aInstituts fémininsxHistoirexOntarioxOntario. 0aRural womenxSocieties, etcxHistoryxOntario. 0aRural womenzOntarioxSocieties, etcxHistory. 0aWomen's institutesxHistoryxOntario. 0aWomen's instituteszOntarioxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357072640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773570726423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773570726/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles